In this thesis we have studied the capability of high level programming language Python to compute the ground state energy of a He atom by using the Quantum Variational Monte Carlo method. A similar implementation was developed in plain C++ and comparisons of performance carried out. Blottleknecks of the plain Python code were identified by profiling and the slow part moved to plain C++ to develop a mixed Python/C++ code. Because of the low gain observed in terms of implementation time and performance, these approaches have been desecahdos. \\
\\
